## 5. Uses Generally Allowed

The following uses are generally allowed when consistent with the repository license and proper attribution is provided.

### 5.1 Personal Learning

You may use repository materials to study structured prompting, prompt engineering systems, documentation design, and framework architecture.

Examples:

- Reading the OPRMT™ Framework Standard
- Studying prompt templates
- Practicing with OPRMT™ prompt structure
- Testing OPRMT™ concepts in private workspaces

### 5.2 Internal Reference

You may reference OPRMT™ materials internally for learning, planning, or workflow improvement.

Examples:

- Using the OPRMT™ sequence to structure internal prompts
- Reviewing component definitions with a team
- Creating internal notes based on public documentation
- Comparing OPRMT™ with other prompt engineering methods

### 5.3 Non-Commercial Educational Discussion

You may discuss, cite, or teach concepts from the public repository when attribution is included and the use does not imply official endorsement.

Examples:

- Referencing OPRMT™ in a class discussion
- Linking to the official repository in a resource list
- Explaining the OPRMT™ structure in a non-commercial workshop
- Writing commentary that identifies OPRMT™ as owned by Michael W. Fleming

### 5.4 Attribution-Based Public Reference

You may reference the framework publicly if attribution is clear.

Recommended attribution:

```text
OPRMT™ Framework created by Michael W. Fleming.
Official materials available through the OPRMT™ repository.
```

---

## 6. Uses Requiring Permission

The following uses require written permission, a separate license, or formal approval from the owner.

### 6.1 Selling OPRMT™ Materials

You may not sell repository materials, copied templates, framework documents, prompt clusters, or derivative commercial packages based substantially on OPRMT™ materials without approval.

Examples requiring permission:

- Selling OPRMT™ prompt packs
- Selling OPRMT™ documentation bundles
- Packaging repository content into a paid course
- Selling templates copied or lightly modified from the repository

### 6.2 Commercial Redistribution

You may not redistribute OPRMT™ materials as part of a paid product, SaaS tool, membership, downloadable bundle, agency package, or client deliverable without permission.

Examples requiring permission:

- Uploading OPRMT™ files into a paid template library
- Including OPRMT™ documents in a subscription product
- Bundling OPRMT™ prompts inside a commercial software tool
- Distributing modified OPRMT™ templates to paying customers

### 6.3 White-Label or Rebranded Use

You may not remove OPRMT™ branding, rename the framework, or present OPRMT™ materials as your own original system.

Not allowed without written permission:

- Rebranding OPRMT™ as another framework
- Removing ownership notices
- Replacing OPRMT™ terminology with a competing brand
- Claiming authorship of OPRMT™ structure or documentation

### 6.4 Official Certification or Training Use

You may not claim to provide official OPRMT™ certification, official OPRMT™ training, or authorized OPRMT™ accreditation without approval.

Restricted claims include:

- “Official OPRMT™ Certified”
- “Authorized OPRMT™ Instructor”
- “OPRMT™ Accredited Program”
- “Certified by OPRMT™”
- “Official OPRMT™ Training Partner”

### 6.5 Commercial Client Services Using OPRMT™ Branding

If you use OPRMT™ branding, terminology, templates, or documentation as part of paid client work, permission may be required depending on scope.

Examples requiring review:

- Selling OPRMT™ implementation services
- Offering OPRMT™ audits as a paid service
- Delivering OPRMT™ branded prompt systems to clients
- Using OPRMT™ documents in client-facing proposals

---

## 7. Uses Not Allowed

The following uses are not allowed unless explicitly approved in writing.

- Claiming ownership of OPRMT™ or related systems
- Removing copyright, trademark, ownership, or attribution notices
- Misrepresenting OPRMT™ as open public-domain material
- Selling copied OPRMT™ repository files
- Creating confusingly similar competing documentation using OPRMT™ branding
- Claiming official endorsement without approval
- Claiming legal, professional, academic, or accreditation status not granted by the owner
- Using OPRMT™ materials in deceptive, harmful, or misleading products
- Using OPRMT™ materials to train or market a competing certification without permission
- Republishing the repository as a commercial product

