## 9. Attribution Requirements

When referencing OPRMT™ materials publicly, include attribution.

Recommended short attribution:

```text
OPRMT™ Framework created by Michael W. Fleming.
```

Recommended extended attribution:

```text
This material references the OPRMT™ Framework, created by Michael W. Fleming. OPRMT™ and related framework materials remain the property of their owner unless otherwise stated in the repository license or usage policy.
```

For web pages, documentation, presentations, articles, or public training references, include a link to the official repository or official OPRMT™ website when available.

---

## 10. Derivative Works

A derivative work is any material substantially based on, adapted from, reorganized from, or modified from OPRMT™ repository content.

Derivative works may include:

- Modified OPRMT™ prompt templates
- Adapted framework guides
- Reformatted documentation packs
- Translated OPRMT™ materials
- Commercial training materials based on OPRMT™ documents
- Prompt libraries using OPRMT™ structure and branding
- Software tools embedding OPRMT™ logic or terminology

Derivative commercial works may require written permission.

Derivative works must not misrepresent ownership, authorship, origin, endorsement, or authorization.

---

## 11. Internal Business Use

Internal business use means using OPRMT™ ideas, structure, or public documentation inside an organization without selling, redistributing, rebranding, or publicly claiming official status.

Internal use may include:

- Structuring internal prompts
- Creating internal AI workflow checklists
- Training employees on structured prompt thinking
- Testing OPRMT™ concepts for operational improvement

Internal business use should preserve attribution when repository materials are copied into internal documents.

Internal business use does not authorize resale, redistribution, white-label use, or certification claims.

